[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626817&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626817&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Here are two points of view, to help fuel the discussion:

1.  The email providers are transparent to the names of the subgroups they
serve.  That is, the fact that xyz.com might be a company that has its
entire domain stored and serviced on mcimail does not need to be visible
to the user community.  Those details are handled via the DNS quite
nicely, just as many off-net (i.e., not directly attached to the
Internet) hosts currently cannot be discerned, through use of the MX
records.  You cannot tell that mail is relayed, e.g., through relay.cs.net.

2.  Alternately, such as for users not in a position to create or use
a domain (if there are any such groups/people), you might observe that
national relay services should be treated differently.  That is, MCI Mail,
Telemail, Compuserve, etc., are the equivalent to PTT's and perhaps
should be at the top of the domain structure.  E.g., dave@xyz.mci.

(I prefer alternative 1, but the case for 2 might be significant.  A
degenerate version of this might be to put these entities under the
'net' domain, resulting in dave@xyz.mci.net.

Dave

